the organisation's image policy and that\nit contains no outstanding critical CVEs.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n4. RESOURCE REQUESTS AND LIMITS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n  ray-head   containers[0].resources:  {} (none configured)\n  ray-worker containers[0].resources:  {} (none configured)\n\nDEVIATION — RISK: Neither deployment has resource requests or limits.\nConsequences:\n  - Pods receive the BestEffort QoS class (lowest priority); they are\n    the first candidates for OOM-kill under memory pressure.\n  - The Kubernetes scheduler cannot make optimal placement decisions.\n  - A misbehaving job can starve other workloads on the same node.\n\nRECOMMENDATION: Before the next change window, add explicit CPU and\nmemory requests and limits to both deployments.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n5. EXPOSED SERVICES AND DASHBOARD\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nService ray-head (ClusterIP):\n  Ports exposed: 6379/TCP  (Ray GCS port only)\n  No NodePort, LoadBalancer, or Ingress found in the namespace.\n\nRay dashboard status:\n  The ray-head startup command contains --include-dashboard=false.\n  The dashboard is explicitly DISABLED and is not exposed on any\n  service port. This is the default/safe posture.\n\nNo deviation from baseline on dashboard exposure.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n6. RAY-HEAD DEPLOYMENT CONFIGURATION\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nCommand (from Deployment spec):\n  ray start --head \\\n    --node-ip-address=\"${MY_POD_IP}\" \\\n    --port=6379 \\\n    --include-dashboard=false \\\n    --num-cpus=0 \\\n    --block\n\nKey settings:\n  --num-cpus=0              Head node will not accept Ray tasks (standard)\n  --port=6379               GCS port (default)\n  --include-dashboard=false Dashboard disabled (default/safe)\n\nEnvironment variables injected:\n  MY_POD_IP  <- status.podIP    (pod IP binding)\n  RAY_NODE_ID <- metadata.uid   (node identity)\n  RAY_RAYLET_PID = \"1\"          (raylet PID hint)\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n7. RAY-WORKER DEPLOYMENT CONFIGURATION\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nCommand (from Deployment spec):\n  ray start --address=ray-head:6379 \\\n    --node-ip-address=\"${MY_POD_IP}\" \\\n    --num-cpus=1 \\\n    --block\n\nKey settings:\n  --address=ray-head:6379   Connects to head via Service DNS (correct)\n  --num-cpus=1              Each worker advertises 1 CPU to Ray scheduler\n\nEnvironment variables: same pattern as ray-head (MY_POD_IP, RAY_NODE_ID,\nRAY_RAYLET_PID).\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n8. ACTIVE CONFIGMAPS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n  kube-root-ca.crt  (1 key — Kubernetes cluster CA, system-managed)\n\nNo application-level ConfigMaps are present. No deviation.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n9. ADDITIONAL OBSERVATIONS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nA. Unmanaged pod: ray-client (rayproject/ray:2.9.0) is running but is\n   not owned by any Deployment, ReplicaSet, or StatefulSet. This pod\n   will not be restarted automatically if it fails and will not be\n   cleaned up by the normal deployment lifecycle. Confirm it is\n   intentional; if it is a leftover test/debug pod, schedule removal\n   after the change window.\n\nB. No HorizontalPodAutoscaler (HPA) for ray-worker. Scaling is manual.\n   Consider HPA if workload is variable.\n\nC. No PodDisruptionBudget (PDB) for ray-worker. A node drain during\n   maintenance could remove the single worker pod with no availability\n   guarantee. Recommend adding a PDB (minAvailable: 1) before